  "text": "Given d , we can obtain the transformed field of view of the camera α as α = 2 arctan(w/d ) (for constant speed g = 0 it corresponds to Equation 4). Note that in order to maintain a constant field of view α during acceleration, different accelerations would be needed in the pinhole and the sensor, as derived by Franklin [CITATION_1] . Figure 6 shows a sequence of an accelerating camera in the cube scene. We can see that, as opposed to the case in which a constant camera speed is used, the reduced field of view due to the Lorentz transform reduces the effect of light aberration observed with a camera at constant speed. This effect is more explicit in Figure 7 , which compares the effect of constant speed and acceleration.",
